Requirement description

Heat map of categorical variables.

https://bmccancer.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12885-019-5768-0 From https://bmccancer.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12885-019-5768-0

Fig. 1 Differential gene expression of 24 matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs) in 15 different cancer types. Fold change and p-values shown were obtained through comparison of unmatched control tissue (N between 11 and 114) to tumor tissue (N between 66 and 1097). Fold change was calculated as the median expression of a gene in tumor divided by the median gene expression in adjacent normal tissue.

Interpretation of the figure

  • 65pvalue
  • pvalue>0.05
  • One gene per row, one cancer type per column
  • Colors are divided into 6 levels: 5 levels of change fold (red up, blue down) and pvalue not significant (white)
  • If pvalue>0.05, it will be white regardless of the change fold
  • When it is white and gray, the words are black; when it is blue and red, the words are white.

Application scenarios

When displaying the results of differential expression of certain genes, continuous variables are often used as numerical values to directly draw heat maps. You can also set it as a categorical variable as in the example text, and use numbers to further annotate it. After becoming a categorical variable, you may see the trend more clearly.

It can also be used to convert and display correlations or other continuous variables.

complexheatmappheatmapFigureYa114ternaryCluster3// Here we use complexheatmap to draw the picture, but you can also use pheatmap to draw the picture. You can refer to FigureYa114ternaryCluster, which is divided into 3 groups (high/low/unchanged) according to the expression level to draw the picture.

Convert continuous variables to categorical variables

Classification rules:

  • logFC5
  • pvalue>0.056
  • First divide into 5 categories according to logFC value;
  • If pvalue>0.05, it will be regarded as the 6th category regardless of the multiple.
## logfc
## Classify logfc
logfcCat <- apply(logfcOrdered, 2, function(x){
    cut(x, breaks = c(-Inf, -2, -1, 1, 2, Inf),
        labels = c("< -2", "-2 - -1", "-1 - 1", "1 - 2", "> 2"))
})
rownames(logfcCat) <- rownames(logfcOrdered)

## 
## Ensure that the order of column names and row names of the two datasets is consistent
if(!identical(rownames(logfcCat), rownames(p.valOrdered))) p.valOrdered <- p.valOrdered[rownames(logfcCat),]
if(!identical(colnames(logfcCat), colnames(p.valOrdered))) p.valOrdered <- p.valOrdered[colnames(logfcCat)]

## P> 0.05 P > 0.05
## Mark data with P> 0.05 as P > 0.05
logfcCat[p.valOrdered >= 0.05] <- "P >= 0.05"

Start drawing

ComplexHeatmap We use ComplexHeatmap to draw, divided into three steps:

  1. logfcCat
  2. cutoff
  5. Define the color of the heat map with the converted logfcCat dataset;
  6. Add numbers to each heat map frame. Since black numbers are not clear in dark colors, the color of the numbers will be adjusted according to different cutoffs;
  7. Add classification annotations on the left;
  8. Draw the picture.

1.

1. Define the color of each classification variable

## 
## Check how many categories there are
unique(matrix(logfcCat, ncol  = 1))
##      [,1]       
## [1,] "> 2"      
## [2,] "1 - 2"    
## [3,] "P >= 0.05"
## [4,] "-2 - -1"  
## [5,] "-1 - 1"   
## [6,] "< -2"
## 
## Define a color for each category
col_cat <- c("> 2" = "#A80C3A", "1 - 2" = "#ED5E57", "-1 - 1" = "#DDD3D2",
             "-2 - -1" = "#6B9AB7", "< -2" = "#2F5B89", "P >= 0.05" = "white")

2. cutoff

2. Customize a function that changes the font color according to the cutoff

When the heat map color is white and gray, the text is black; when it is blue and red, the text is white.

So we define a function that contains two data sets

cell_fun <- function(logfc, dataP, logfcCutoff = 1, PCutoff = 0.05, 
                     darkcol = "black", lightcol = "white", digit = 2, fontsize  = 6){
    function(j, i, x, y, width, height, fill){
        if(abs(logfc[i,j]) > logfcCutoff & dataP[i,j] < PCutoff){
            grid.text(round(logfc, digit)[i, j], x, y, 
                      gp = gpar(fontsize = fontsize, col  = lightcol))
        }else{
            grid.text(round(logfc, digit)[i, j], x, y, 
                      gp = gpar(fontsize = fontsize, col  = darkcol))
        }
    }
}

The parameters of the function include

  • logfc: logfc
  • dataP: P
  • logfcCutoffPCutoffcutoff
  • darkcollightcol
  • digit:
  • fontsize:
  • logfc: logfc data set
  • dataP: P value data set
  • logfcCutoff and PCutoff cutoff values
  • darkcol and lightcol: light and dark font colors
  • digit: the number of decimal places for displaying data in the heat map box
  • fontsize: the size of the font color in the heat map box

3.

3. Add annotations

There will be an annotation for the gene next to the heat map. We need to define the annotation information

## 
## Define the color of the annotation information
an_col <- c("#ED1450", "#FCCA02", "#A7CE35", "#2C92DA", "#59574A", "#FFF8AD", "#A2238E", "#BCBDBF")
names(an_col) <- unique(genetype$type)

## 
## Define the annotation information
row_an <-  HeatmapAnnotation(type = genetype$type, ## ##Content of the annotation information
                             show_annotation_name = F, ## 
## Whether to display the title of the annotation
                             col = list(type = an_col), ## 
## The color of the annotation information
                             show_legend = T,  ## 
 ## Whether to display the description of the annotation 
                             annotation_legend_param = list(title = "MMP Subtype"), ## 
## The title of the annotation legend
                             which = "row") # 
#Annotate rows or columns

4.

4. Unified drawing

Finally, we can combine all the data together to draw the picture

pdf("rankHeatmap.pdf", width = 8, height = 4)
Heatmap(matrix = logfcCat, 
        name = "logFC", # #Title of the main legend
        rect_gp = gpar(col = "NA", lwd = 1), #col = "grey" #No border, or use col = "grey" to draw a gray border
        col = col_cat, # #Heatmap color
        row_names_side = "left", 
        cell_fun = cell_fun(logfcOrdered, p.valOrdered), 
        row_names_gp = gpar(fontsize = 8), # #Gene name
        column_names_gp = gpar(fontsize = 8), # #Tumor type font size
        column_names_rot = 45, #45 #Tumor type at 45 degrees
        left_annotation = row_an) # #Left gene classification, if not drawn, this parameter will be filtered out
